result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both OWI (5th or 6th) [Modifiers: General Alcohol Concentration Enhancer] and Operating w/ PAC (5th or 6th) [Modifiers: Modifier-Alcohol Conc. (.20-.249)]. The defendant was found guilty of both charges. Because Wisconsin law provides for only one penalty even if there is a conviction on both, no additional penalty has been imposed as a result of the second charge.

  • Elliot R Nehls was found guilty of OWI (5th or 6th) [Modifiers: General Alcohol Concentration Enhancer], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).
  • Elliot R Nehls was found guilty of Operating w/ PAC (5th or 6th) [Modifiers: Modifier-Alcohol Conc. (.20-.249)], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(b).
  • Elliot R Nehls was found guilty of Operating While Revoked (Rev due to alc/contr subst/refusal), an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 343.44(1)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.
